## Week 2 — Data Generation + S3 Bronze Upload

Generated realistic fake e-commerce data using Python to simulate
a raw OLTP source database for ShopMax.

### Scripts Written
- generate_customers.py → 1000 customers (ID: 1-1000)
- generate_sellers.py → 200 sellers (ID: 1000-1199)
- generate_products.py → 500 products (ID: 10000-10499)
- generate_orders.py → 10,000 orders (ID: 100000-109999)
- generate_order_items.py → ~50,000 order items
- generate_payments.py → 10,000 payments (ID: 50000+)

### Tools Used
Python, Faker, Pandas, random, boto3

### What Was Done
- Designed raw data columns by thinking like the website — not the star schema
- Generated dimensions first (customers, sellers, products) because facts reference them
- order_items reads from orders.csv to maintain data consistency
- payments reads from orders.csv for matching amounts and dates
- All six CSVs uploaded to s3://shopmax-datalake/Bronze_layer/ using boto3

### Key Insight
Raw data shape ≠ Star schema shape. Bronze layer holds data as the
application database captured it. Star schema is applied later in
Snowflake via dbt.
